{[%evp 0,11,22,24,25,4,39,26,26,26,34,17,9,24]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3. Nc3 Bg7
4. e4 d6 5. f3 O-O 6. Be3 {The most popular move.} c5 {Once again I prefer the
Benoni setup.} 7. d5 {A rare move compare to 7.Nge2 and 7.dxc5. Nowadays the
theory proved that Black is doing great here.} e6 8. Qd2 ({After:} 8.
Nge2 exd5 9. cxd5 Nbd7 10. Ng3 h5 {Transpose to the previous chapter with 6.
Nge2.}) 8... exd5 9. cxd5 a6 {Almost always is good to include this move.} 10.
a4 Re8 {The critical position. White has two main options here.} 11. Nge2 {
The main move, although I believe Black has zero problems here.} (11. Bd3 $6 {
Once again, this is not the optimal square for the bishop.} Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]}
12. Nge2 Ne5 13. O-O Nxd3 14. Qxd3 Nd7 {[%cal Gd7e5]} 15. f4 Nf6 $1 $15 {
[%csl Re4] I believe Black is already better.}) (11. Be2 $5 {A very awkward, but
interesting move. Recently was played by very strong players, including Jan
Duda. The idea is to wait for 11...Nbd7 and then to play 12.Nh3 followed by Nf2.
} h5 {A good waiting move.} ({Another interesting waiting move is:} 11... Qe7)
12. h4 {[%cal Gg1h3] The most logical response to h5.} ({The alternatives are:
} 12. Bd1 $6 {This looks a bit too slow for White.} Nbd7 13. Nge2 Ne5 {[%cal
Ge5c4]} 14. b3 {White must prevent Nc4.} b6 $1 {[%cal Ga8b8,Gb6b5] Black has
time for this slow,but very strong plan.} 15. O-O Rb8 16. Bc2 b5 $15 {Black
was better in the game: Yevseev, D (2503)-Sakaev, K (2649) St Petersburg 1999.})
(12. Bh6 {This is another logical move.} Bh8 {Of course the bishop is
important.} 13. Bf4 ({Another option is:} 13. Nh3 Bxh3 14. gxh3 {Looks strange
for White, but in fact, the game is still very double-edged.} Nbd7 15. O-O Rc8
16. Kh1 c4 $132 {With a very sharp game in the game: Schlenther, M (2517)
-Nichols, S (2372) LSS email 2020.}) 13... Nh7 {The solution of the engines.} ({
Also possible is:} 13... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Gb8d7,Gc5c4]}) 14. h4 Bd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]
} 15. Bd3 Qe7 16. Nge2 Bf6 17. g3 Nd7 $13 {Black was doing fine in the game:
Figlio,G (2484)-Sasikiran,K (2553) ICCF email 2020.}) (12. a5 {Here Black is
completely fine after:} b5 13. axb6 Qxb6 $132) 12... Qc7 $5 {Another waiting
move.} ({The other options are also playable:} 12... Nh7 13. g3 f5 14. Nh3 ({
May be interesting is:} 14. Bd3 $5) 14... fxe4 $6 ({Here better was:} 14...
Bxc3 $1 15. bxc3 fxe4 16. Nf4 Qe7 $13 {with a very complicated game.}) 15. Nxe4
Bf5 {This position occurred in the game Duda, J (2738)-Naroditsky, D (2623)
chess24.com INT 2021. Here White could take advantage after:} 16. Nhf2 $14)
(12... Nbd7 {Is also an option.} 13. Nh3 Ne5 14. Nf2 Bd7 15. O-O Rb8 16. a5 b5
17. axb6 Rxb6 $11 {Looks like a very playable position.}) 13. Kf2 {Still
waiting for Nbd7.} ({If} 13. Bh6 {then} Bh8) ({Clearly worse is:} 13. Nh3 $6
Bxh3 14. Rxh3 Nbd7 $15 {[%csl Re1] Black is better.}) (13. a5 b5 14. axb6 Qxb6
$132 {Black lost a tempo, but this does not make a big difference.}) (13. g4 {
