possible is} 6... e5 $5) 7. a3 cxd4 (7... Bg4 $5) 8. Nxd4 ({After} 8. exd4 $6 {
Black should immediately strike with} e5 $1 9. Be2 e4 10. Nfd2 Nc6 $17 {
Black has a huge advantage.}) 8... a5 9. Be2 axb4 (9... Nc6) 10. axb4 Rxa1 11.
Bxa1 Qb6 12. Qb3 Nc6 $11 {Black enjoys comfortable equality.}) 6... c5 $5 {
This is the most natural way of obtaining counterplay.} 7. a3 (7. bxc5 dxc5 8.
O-O cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 10. c4 Qb6 $15 {[%csl Rd4][%cal Gf6e4,Gf8d8] Black is
already better. He will increase the pressure on the central hanging pawns
with ...Rd8 and ...Ne4.}) 7... cxd4 ({Another option is} 7... Qb6 $5 8. Nbd2
cxb4 9. Nc4 Qc7 10. axb4 Bf5 $11) 8. Nxd4 a5 $11 {An important part of Black's
strategy. Besides activating the a8-rook, Black creates queenside targets.})
3... Bg7 4. Bb2 O-O ({The immediate} 4... c5 $5 {is possible as well. For
instance, after} 5. dxc5 Na6 {Black has a decent counterplay.}) 5. e3 ({
Less precise is} 5. g3 $6 {when the energetic} c5 $1 {creates problems for
White.} 6. d5 ({Even worse is} 6. dxc5 $6 Qa5+ 7. Nbd2 Qxc5 $15 {[%csl Rf2]
[%cal Gf6g4] when Black is better. The threat of ...Ng4 is pretty annoying.})
6... Qa5+ $1 {This intermediate check spoils White's coordination.} 7. Bc3 Qb6
{[%csl Rc3]} 8. Bg2 e6 $15 {White cannot hold the centre. His c3-bishop is
clearly misplaced.}) 5... b6 $5 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc7c5] In my opinion, this is the
most flexible setup. After putting the bishop on b7, Black will play either ...
c7-c5 or ...d7-d5.} 6. Be2 ({A high-profile game saw} 6. g3 Bb7 ({In my
opinion, the standard} 6... c5 $5 {would have been a decent option as well.})
7. Bg2 d5 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nbd2 (9. c4 c5) 9... c5 10. Qe2 Rc8 11. c4 dxc4 12.
bxc4 e6 13. a4 Ne4 $11 {The position was dynamically equal in the game ½-½ 
