{[%evp 0,20,31,30,30,26,44,45,45,40,40,40,42,29,49,40,34,33,33,35,30,-3,27]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Nc3 d5 4. Bf4 {This move marks the beginning of the
so-called Jobava London. After achieving solid central control, White often
launches a kingside activity with the advance h2-h4-h5. Another typical idea
is Nb5 with the idea to force the black knight into the passive a6-square.} ({
The alternative} 4. Bg5 $6 {gives Black an important tempo -} Ne4 $1 5. Bf4 ({
Worse is} 5. Nxe4 $6 dxe4 $17 {[%csl Rd4] when the d4-pawn is immediately
getting vulnerable.}) 5... Nxc3 6. bxc3 c5 7. e3 Bg7 $15 {[%csl Rc3][%cal
Gb8c6,Gd8a5] Black is already better in view of White damaged pawn structure.
The next moves will be ...Nc6 and ...Qa5.}) 4... Bg7 5. e3 {Before going for
active actions, White should develop and stabilize the centre.} ({The immediate
} 5. h4 $6 {is well met by} c5 $1 {when Black quickly organizes his conterplay.
The following lines are quite illustrative.} 6. e3 ({Not advisable is} 6. dxc5
O-O 7. Qd2 Nc6 $15 {[%cal Gd8a5,Gd5d4,Gf6e4] Black managed to develop a
terrible initiative. The immediate threat is ...d5-d4 followed by ...Ne4 and ..
.Qa5. It's clear that h2-h4 was premature.}) 6... O-O 7. Ne5 Nc6 {[%cal Gd8b6]
This is an important move in Black's strategy. The d4-pawn is already under
pressure. Black is ready to proceed with ...Qb6.} 8. h5 Qb6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10.
hxg6 fxg6 $15 {Black is better in view of his superior development and central
pressure.}) ({Another interesting idea is} 5. Qd2 {[%cal Gf4h6] planning to
exchange the bishops via h6. In my opinion, the simplest solution would be} O-O
(5... Ne4 $5) (5... c5 $5) 6. Bh6 Ne4 $5 {This is the key idea. Black makes
use of the position of the white queen.} 7. Nxe4 {The only way to fight for an
advantage.} ({Harmless is} 7. Qe3 Nxc3 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Qxc3 Qd6 10. e3 a5 $11 {
when Black enjoys comfortable equality.}) 7... dxe4 8. Bxg7 Kxg7 9. Ng5 ({
A typical mistake would be} 9. Ne5 $6 {when Black can play} b5 $1 {[%csl Re5]
taking the c4-square for the white knight.}) 9... f5 {White should already
take care of his knight.} 10. h4 ({The alternative} 10. O-O-O {is worse. Black
can play} h6 11. Nh3 Qd5 12. Kb1 Be6 13. b3 Qd6 14. Nf4 Bf7 15. e3 Nd7 $15 {
Black is already better. At some point, he will play ...e7-e5.}) 10... h6 11.
Nh3 e5 {Just in time! Black prevents the white knight from reaching the
f4-square.} 12. e3 ({After} 12. dxe5 $6 Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 Nc6 $15 {Black will
comfortably regain the pawn. His advantage is out of question.}) 12... Qxh4 {
Accepting the challenge! It's not easy for White to prove compensation.} 13.
O-O-O Qe7 14. f4 $1 exd4 {This move more or less forces a draw by repetition.
The alternatives are risky.} (14... exf3 $6 15. gxf3 $40 {[%csl Rg7][%cal
Gd2h2]}) (14... exf4 15. Nxf4 Nd7 16. g4 Nf6 17. gxf5 Bxf5 18. Bc4 $13) 15.
Qxd4+ Qf6 16. Qc5 Nc6 17. Bb5 Qe7 18. Qc3+ Qf6 $11) (5. Nb5 {This is a typical
idea in the Jobava London. Now, the black knight will have to occupy the
inferior a6-square.} Na6 6. e3 ({Sometimes, White starts with} 6. h3 {
defending against the potential ...Nh5. In this case, however, Black has
enough time to organize his counterplay -} c6 7. Na3 ({White's problem is that
Black is ready to meet} 7. Nc3 $6 {with} Ne4 $1 {with the following possible
line} 8. e3 Nxc3 9. bxc3 Qa5 10. Qd2 Nc5 {[%cal Gc5e4]} 11. c4 Qa3 $15 {
Black is already better. White should reckon with the threat of ...Ne4.}) 7...
Qb6 8. Rb1 O-O 9. e3 Bf5 10. Be2 c5 11. O-O Rac8 $11 {Black has nothing to
worry about.}) 6... O-O {I prefer the setups based on ...Ne4.} ({Of course,} 
6... Nh5 $5 7. Bg5 O-O {is possible as well.}) 7. h3 Ne4 $5 {This was my
initial idea.} ({After} 7... c6 8. Nc3 Qb6 9. Rb1 {White has nothing to worry
about.}) 8. Nd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Gb5c3] White immediately challenges the knight.
After taking on e4, he can play Nc3 with a tempo.} ({It's very important to
point out that after} 8. Be2 c6 9. Na3 Qb6 10. Rb1 {Black has} Qb4+ $1 {
spoiling White's coordination.} 11. c3 (11. Kf1 $6 f6 12. c3 Qa5 $17) 11...
Nxc3 12. bxc3 Qxa3 13. O-O Nb8 $15 {White does not have sufficient
compensation for the pawn.}) ({The attempt to stabilize the centre with} 8. c3
{does not work quite well. Black can play} c6 9. Na3 f6 $1 {[%cal Ge7e5]
planning to gain space in the centre with ...e7-e5.} 10. Be2 (10. Bxa6 bxa6 11.
O-O Qb6 $132) 10... e5 11. Bh2 Nc7 12. O-O exd4 13. cxd4 (13. Nxd4 f5 14. c4
Ne6 $11) 13... f5 14. Nb1 Ne6 15. Nbd2 c5 $1 $132 {Black has more than
sufficient counterplay.}) 8... c6 $5 {This is Black's most precise
continuation.} ({In one of my games, I played} 8... Nxd2 9. Qxd2 c6 10. Nc3 Nc7
11. O-O-O b5 $13 {with unclear position. ½-½ (66) Kryakvin,D (2577)
-Cheparinov,I (2667) Tornelo INT 2021}) 9. Nxe4 dxe4 10. Nc3 c5 {Without this
dynamic move, Black is just statically worse.} 11. Nxe4 ({Another important
line is} 11. Bxa6 bxa6 12. O-O cxd4 13. exd4 Bxd4 14. Bh6 Re8 15. Qe1 Bb7 16.
Rd1 e5 17. Nxe4 Qh4 18. Nd6 Qxh6 19. Nxb7 Bxb2 $11 {Once again, the position
is dynamically balanced.}) 11... cxd4 12. exd4 Nb4 ({Another decent
possibility is} 12... Qd5 $5 13. f3 Bf5) 13. c3 {The most natural reaction.} ({
Worse is} 13. Be3 $6 Bxd4 14. a3 Bxe3 15. axb4 {½-½ (59) Harikrishna,P (2705)
-Grandelius, N (2635) chess24.com INT 2022. At this point, Black could have
played} Bb6 16. Bd3 Bf5 $17 {with a huge advantage.}) 13... Bf5 14. f3 (14. Qe2
$6 Nd5 15. Bh2 Qa5 $40 {[%cal Gd5c3,Gf5e4]}) 14... Nd5 15. Bg3 {White tries to
keep his control of the e5-square.} ({After} 15. Bg5 Qc7 16. Qd2 h6 17. Bh4 e5
18. Bg3 Rad8 $44 {Black is obviously better.}) 15... e5 $1 {This energetic
move seems to be the best way of developing the initiative.} 16. dxe5 Bxe4 17.
fxe4 Bxe5 $1 {This is the key idea behind Black's 15...e5.} 18. Bxe5 {With
this move, White accepts the draw.} ({An alternative is} 18. Qf3 Bxg3+ 19. Qxg3
Re8 20. Bd3 {Once again, energetic play allows Black to equalize.} (20. O-O-O
Rxe4) 20... Nf4 $1 21. O-O-O Rxe4 $1 22. Bxe4 Ne2+ 23. Kc2 Nxg3 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8
25. Re1 Re8 26. Kd3 $11 {with a draw.}) 18... Qh4+ 19. Kd2 Qh6+ 20. Ke1 Qh4+
$11) 5... O-O 6. Be2 ({After} 6. Nb5 Na6 {we have a transposition to 5.Nb5.}) (
{In case of} 6. Bd3 {[%csl Rd3] Black obtains a good position with natural
moves -} c5 7. h3 (7. O-O Bg4 8. Be2 cxd4 9. exd4 Nc6 $11) 7... b6 8. O-O Bb7
9. Re1 Nbd7 $11 {with comfortable equality.}) ({After} 6. h3 {a good idea is}
c5) 6... c5 7. O-O {White just completes the development. Of course, with such
a play he cannot fight for an advantage.} ({Taking the pawn} 7. dxc5 {does not
work quite well after} Qa5 ({or even} 7... Nbd7 $5) 8. O-O ({Another typical
reaction is} 8. Nd2 Qxc5 9. Nb3 Qc6 10. O-O b6 $11 {with equality.}) 8... Qxc5
9. Nd4 e6 10. Nb3 Qe7 11. e4 Rd8 $11 {Black enjoys comfortable counterplay.}) (
{After} 7. Qd2 {a good idea would be} Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Bxf3 cxd4 10. exd4 Nc6
11. O-O e6 $11 {This kind of Carlsbad pawn structure is quite favourable for
Black, The c3-knight is obviously misplaced. In the next moves, Black can
consider ...Rc8 followed by ...Na5-c4.}) ({Too slow is} 7. h3 {when after} Ne4
$1 {Black obtains decent counterplay.}) (7. Ne5 cxd4 8. exd4 Nc6 9. O-O {
transposes to 7.0-0.}) 7... cxd4 (7... b6 $5) 8. exd4 ({After} 8. Nxd4 $6 a6 {
it's not clear how White can compensate for Black domination in the centre.})
8... Nc6 9. Ne5 Bf5 ({Challenging the knight with} 9... Nd7 $5 {is also an
option.}) 10. Re1 (10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Qd2 c5 12. Be5 Rc8 $11) 10... Rc8 $11 {
Black enjoys comfortable equality.} *

