{[%evp 0,40,5,56,31,23,59,-8,11,-33,-14,-8,-1,5,8,-21,-12,-25,-28,-24,-21,-4,
-11,-3,4,3,-7,16,25,25,46,32,46,49,29,30,29,26,21,36,32,46,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Nf3 g6 3. Nbd2 {This move has recently seen some spike in popularity on GM
level. White wants to follow with e2-e4. Also, it is planning to restrict
Black's dark-squared bishop by means of c2-c3. Therefore, the most principled
reply is} d5 {preventing e2-e4 and restricting the d2-knight.} 4. b4 {[%cal
Gc1b2,Ge2e3,Gc2c4] This is the critical move. White gains space on the
queenside and prepares Bb2 followed by e2-e3 and c2-c4.} ({Too harmless is} 4.
b3 {when a possible continuation would be} Bg7 5. Bb2 O-O 6. e3 b6 $5 {[%cal
Gc8b7,Gb8d7,Gc7c5] In my opinion, this is the most natural continuation.
Black's plan is really simple - ...Bb7 followed by ...Nbd7, and ...c7-c5.} ({
Of course, also possible is} 6... Bf5) 7. Be2 ({In his game against Caruana,
Nakamura played} 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. c4 c5 10. Qe2 (10. Rc1 Rc8 11. Re1
e6 $11) 10... e6 11. Rfd1 {This position was reached in the game 1-0 (53)
Nakamura,H (2786)-Caruana,F (2802) Chess.com INT 2017. Now, the simplest would
have been} Rc8 12. Rac1 cxd4 13. exd4 Re8 $11 {with comfortable equality.})
7... Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. c4 c5 10. Rc1 (10. Qc2 Rc8) 10... Rc8 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6,
Gf8e8] Black has nothing to worry about.}) 4... Bg7 5. e3 ({Another natural
continuation would be} 5. Bb2 {In this case, Black follows the same strategy
as in the main line.} O-O 6. e3 a5 {An important part of Black's strategy. We
should challenge White's queenside structure before he develops his pieces.} 7.
b5 a4 8. Ba3 {Blocking the pawn at the cost of an important tempo. Now, Black
will start preparing ...e7-e5.} ({After} 8. c4 $6 c6 $1 9. bxc6 Nxc6 $15 {
Black is already slightly better in view of his better development.}) ({
Harmless is} 8. Rb1 {when a possible line would be} Bf5 9. Bd3 (9. h3 Be4) 9...
Ne4 10. O-O Nd7 11. Qe2 c6 $11 {with equality.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Be2 Re8 $5 {
[%cal Ge7e5] Black is ready to proceed with ...e7-e5.} 10. O-O (10. c4 e5)
10... e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Rxe5 13. Nf3 Re8 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] Even though
the position is objectively equal, I would take Black.}) 5... a5 $5 {We should
play this move without wasting too much time.} (5... O-O 6. c4) 6. b5 c5 7.
bxc6 Nxc6 8. Be2 {For the time being, White just needs to complete the
development.} ({After} 8. Bb5 O-O 9. O-O Bf5 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Ba3 Ne8 $5 {
[%cal Ge8d6]} 12. c4 Nd6 $11 {Black enjoys comfortable equality.}) 8... O-O 9.
O-O Bf5 {The most precise continuation. White should now reckon with the
threat of ...Nb4.} 10. c4 {The most ambitious option.} ({In case of} 10. Ba3 $2
Nb4 $1 {[%csl Rc2]} 11. Ne1 Qc7 $15 {Black is already slightly better.}) ({
The simple development with} 10. Bb2 {does not create any problems for Black.
For example, afetr} Qc7 11. a4 ({or} 11. c4 Nb4 12. Ne5 Nd7 13. Nxd7 Qxd7 14.
a3 Bc2 15. Qc1 Bd3 $11) 11... Rfc8 12. c3 (12. Nh4 Bd7) 12... e5 $11 {Black is
doing perfectly fine.}) ({Another passive move is} 10. c3 Qc7 11. a4 e5 12. Ba3
Rfc8 $11 {Black had no problems in the game ½-½ (25) Aronian, L (2765)
-Vachier Lagrave,M (2778) Saint Louis 2019}) 10... Nb4 {[%cal Gb4c2,Gf5c2]} 11.
Qb3 {Only this continuation requires some precision from Black. Now, the
threat is a2-a3.} ({After} 11. Bb2 Rc8 12. Qb3 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Bc2 14. Qa3 Ne4
$15 {Black was already slightly better in the game ½-½ (49) Theodorou, N 
(2577)-Vachier Lagrave,M (2761) Warsaw 2021}) 11... Bc2 $1 {As it will become
clear a bit later, forcing the queen back to b2 is very important.} 12. Qb2 Qc7
$1 {This is a nice prophylactic against a2-a3.} ({After} 12... dxc4 $2 13. Nxc4
Be4 14. Bd2 $16 {Black had a huge advantage in the game ½-½ (96) Kuzubov, Y 
(2636)-Cheparinov,I (2670) Douglas 2019}) 13. a3 ({To a repetition leads} 13.
Ne5 Bf5 14. Ndf3 Nc2 15. Rb1 Nb4 $11) 13... Bd3 {We can now see the point
behind 11...Bc2. The d3-square is available now.} 14. Bxd3 Nxd3 15. Qb3 ({
Another interesting, although not forced, line is} 15. Qb5 dxc4 ({Black can
also play.} 15... Qc6 $5) 16. Nxc4 Rac8 17. Nb6 Nxc1 18. Nxc8 Rxc8 19. Kh1 Ne4
20. Qb1 Nxf2+ $1 21. Rxf2 Qc3 22. Qxb7 (22. Rf1 Nb3 23. Ra2 Qxe3 $44) 22... Rc7
23. Qa8+ Rc8 $11 {with a draw.}) 15... dxc4 16. Nxc4 Rfc8 17. Qxd3 Qxc4 18.
Qxc4 Rxc4 19. Rb1 Rb8 20. Bd2 a4 $11 {[%cal Gf6e4] The position is equal but
Black still has chances to outplay his opponent. His next move is going to be .
..Ne4.} *

