{[%evp 0,22,23,21,35,30,68,51,48,48,48,38,51,32,32,4,25,11,4,4,12,-46,-12,-31,
22]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 g6 3. Bf4 Bg7 4. e3 {In this chapter, we will briefly
discuss the London System. I will provide an ambitious setup, so that you can
play for a win with Black.} O-O 5. h3 {Usually, White plays this move in the
London System. The idea is to make the h2-square available for the bishop in
case of ...Nh5.} ({Another option is} 5. Nbd2 {In this case, Black's setup
remains basically the same.} d6 6. c3 ({After} 6. h3 {I prefer} Nfd7 $5 {
Immediately preparing ...e7-e5. Later on, Black can further expand on the
kingside by means of ...f7-f5.} 7. c3 e5 8. Bh2 Kh8 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 9. Be2 Qe7
10. O-O f5 $132 {In this complicated position, Black has more than sufficient
counterplay.}) 6... Nc6 7. Be2 Qe8 {Once again, Black is going for ...e7-e5.}
8. h3 e5 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Bg3 a5 {[%cal Gf6d7,Ge8e7,Gd7c5] This move is an
important part in Black's strategy. He is ready to proceed with ...Nd7
followed by ...Qe7, and ...Nc5. The idea of ...a7-a5 is to prevent White from
gaining space on the queenside.} 11. O-O Nd7 12. Qc2 Qe7 $11 {Black enjoys
comfortable equality.}) (5. Be2 d6 6. h3 {transposes to 5.h3.}) 5... d6 6. Be2
{This is White's most popular choice.} ({After} 6. Bc4 {Black should play} c5
$5 {[%cal Gb8c6,Gd8b6] With a bishop on c4, the advance ...e7-e5 is becoming
riskier. Therefore, Black starts playing on the queenside. He is planning to
proceed with ...Nc6 followed by ...Qb6.} 7. O-O Nc6 8. c3 Qb6 9. Qc1 Re8 $5 {
[%cal Ge7e5] The idea of this move is to follow with ...cxd4, and ...e7-e5,
thus opening up the position.} (9... Bf5 10. Nbd2) 10. Nbd2 cxd4 11. exd4 ({
After} 11. cxd4 Bf5 {[%cal Ga8c8,Gc8c1] followed by ...Rc8, White will face
huge problems in view of his misplaced queen.}) 11... e5 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Be3
Qc7 $11 {Black's central majority can be very powerful in such positions.})
6... Nc6 7. c3 {This is a prophylactic against the immediate ...e7-e5.} ({After
} 7. O-O {Black can play} e5 8. Bh2 ({The point is that} 8. dxe5 {will be met
by} Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gg7b2] That's why White should start with 7.c3.}) 8... exd4
9. exd4 Re8 $11) 7... Nd7 8. Bh2 e5 9. O-O (9. b4 a6 10. a4 f5) 9... f5 10. b4
a6 11. a4 {This typical London position arose in the game 0-1 (29) Nguyen, N 
(2639)-Firouzja,A (2682) Xingtai 2019. Now, the most precise would have been}
g5 $1 $132 {[%cal Gg5g4] planning ...g5-g4. Black can already think of
overtaking the initiative.} *

